      "abstract": "Abstract This paper discusses the contributions history can make to educational administration and how history needs to be conceptualised as a humanities discipline to serve this purpose, including two aspects of the field of particular relevance to educational administration and leadership, biography and comparative studies. The value of history is presented in its interpretive power, in both investigating the particular through individual cases and how these are related to larger societal forces of change producing explanation, establishing causal relations, and achieving understanding as Verstehen in its full hermeneutic sense. Notes 1. Nietzsche, Friedrich. On the Advantage and Disadvantage of History for Life. Indianapolis: Hackett, 1980 [1874], 7. 2. Or even political economy in the case of Marxist and Critical Theory writers. 3. For a discussion of the central question as it pertains to administration, see Samier Eugenie. \"Demandarinisation in the New Public Management: Examining Changing Administrative Authority from a Weberian Perspective.\" In Max Webers Herrschaftssoziologie: Studien zu Entstehung und Wirkung. edited by E. Hanke and W. J. Mommsen. T\u00fcbingen: Mohr/Siebeck, 2001: 235\u2013263; \"Toward a Weberian Public Administration: The Infinite Web of History, Values, and Authority in Administrative Mentalities.\" Halduskultuur: Administrative Culture. \u0410\u2202\u043cu\u043ducmpamu\u0431\u043da\u044f \u043ay\u043b\u044amypa\u044e. Verwaltungskultur. Hallintokulttuuri [An Interdisciplinary Public Administration Journal], 6 (2005): 60\u201393. 4. Hennis, Wilhelm. Max Weber: Essays in Reconstruction. London: Allyn & Unwin, 1988, 183. 5. Samier, Eugenie. \"Toward Public Administration as a Humanities Discipline: A Humanistic Manifesto.\" Halduskultuur: Administrative Culture. \u0410\u2202\u043cu\u043ducmpamu\u0431\u043da\u044f \u043ay\u043b\u044amypa\u044e. Verwaltungskultur. Hallintokulttuuri [An Interdisciplinary Public Administ